Germany: an expensive budgetary fetish
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
It was Germany that insisted on integrating this principle into the criteria set out in the Maastricht Treaty, which defines the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a political regime shift.
Thus, the independence of the Banque de France was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against joining the euro during the 1992 referendum on the Maastricht Treaty.
In today's Germany, however, it has become commonplace, if one can say so, to put pressure on the central bank.
Since several months, even the Minister of Finance, Wolfgang Schäuble, regularly comments on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schäuble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes the central bank's independence.
If he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price stability", in the old Bundesbank jargon), he nonetheless advises on the tools the ECB should use and how it should handle them to achieve such a goal.
We have precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then German Minister of Finance, offered his advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's objective was to ultimately create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with his characteristic Dutch brevity, replied that it was not incongruous for a politician to express an opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "Yet," he added, "it would be entirely abnormal to take [his] suggestions into account."
Since several months, Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes the central bank's independence.
The respect for monetary policy independence has long been a central element of Germany's Stabilitätkultur ("stability culture").
The founding act of the Bundesbank's reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's urgings in 1956 to restrain interest rate increases.
At that time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was about to create the Fifth Republic, with the Banque de France reporting to the Minister of Finance.
But that was another time.
Following various crises that have shaken the EMU, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Is the old dogma no longer valid?
Europe remains highly vulnerable; the median resident of the EMU has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming is that we are nearing a critical situation.
The United States, however, do better.
Despite a difficult-to-manage political deadlock, they managed to address the macro-economic issue (the weakness of overall demand) by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also handled their banking problems better, which, at first, were much more severe than in Europe.
(There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both domains.)
The stronger an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the better able they are to fulfill their function: financing the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is more threatened by the lack of support from the population than by the good advice of a finance minister.
And in fact, the famous independence of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, particularly in Germany, calling for increasing pressures on it.
But the greatest threat to the independence of the ECB lies in the unbearable burden weighing on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is called upon to stabilize production, the more central banks are effectively constrained to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course and allow the economy to stagnate, or even worse).
The political result of this is a clear regression towards nationalism, both right-wing and left-wing, in all EMU countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the dance, with its obsession with the schwarze Null and budgetary balance, come rain or shine.
In Germany, deficits are viewed negatively not only from an arithmetic standpoint but also morally, even though this defies sound economic sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the main German experts in public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, forged a "golden rule" according to which current expenditures should be financed, on average, by current revenues.
Public spending, and the resources it requires, are justified by their usefulness.
This means that investments aimed at improving productivity – capital expenditures – can be financed with debt, the service of which is ensured by the growth of revenues and the base of associated tax receipts.
This traditional approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and capital expenditures, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
It is crucial because in Germany, around 50% of public sector capital expenditures are managed at this level (the proportion is decreasing, since the municipal share was two-thirds in the early 1990s).
These expenses are consistent with the support for the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (mittlestand).
But compared to the early 1990s and in constant prices, investment expenditures have fallen by about 15%.
For more than a decade, they have been insufficient to maintain the stock of capital.
If this is not how we prepare for the future, this is how we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In brief, the schwarze Null goes against the intended goal.
Old infrastructure (though not as much as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Moreover, the fiscal frugality of German leaders extends beyond Germany’s borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which lacks exchange rates to accommodate national particularisms.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But blaming the only institution willing to "do what it takes" to get the EMU back on track is a very bad idea.
That states use the fiscal space they have to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, enjoys a certain degree of maneuvering room.
